Solution: The problem requires approximating \(P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) where \(\bar{X}\) is the sample mean of a random sample of size 12 from a uniform distribution on the interval \((0,1)\).

Using the Central Limit Theorem, the sample mean \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed. The population mean is \(\mu = 0.5\) and the population variance is \(\sigma^2 = 1/12\). Thus, the mean of \(\bar{X}\) is \(0.5\) and the variance is \(\sigma^2 / n = (1/12)/12 = 1/144\), so the standard deviation is \(1/12\).

The probability is \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\). Standardizing to the standard normal variable \(Z\):

- At \(\bar{X} = 0.5\), \(Z = (0.5 - 0.5)/(1/12) = 0\).
- At \(\bar{X} = 2/3 \approx 0.6667\), \(Z = (0.6667 - 0.5)/(1/12) = (1/6)/(1/12) = 2\).

This gives \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\), where \(Z\) is standard normal. Using the standard normal distribution:
- \(\Phi(2) \approx 0.9772\)
- \(\Phi(0) = 0.5\)
- \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = 0.9772 - 0.5 = 0.4772\)

Rounding to three significant figures, the probability is approximately 0.477.

