Problem:  If $P(A)=0.8, P(B)=0.5$, and $P(A \cup B)=0.9$. What is $P(A \cap B)$? The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The formula for the union of two events is \( P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B) \).  
Given \( P(A) = 0.8 \), \( P(B) = 0.5 \), and \( P(A \cup B) = 0.9 \), substitute the values:  
\( 0.9 = 0.8 + 0.5 - P(A \cap B) \).  
Simplify: \( 0.9 = 1.3 - P(A \cap B) \).  
Solve for \( P(A \cap B) \): \( P(A \cap B) = 1.3 - 0.9 = 0.4 \).  

The result is a probability, so no units are required. The value 0.4 is exact and does not require rounding.  

