The solution to the problem involves finding the probability of at least one match when a fair $n$-sided die is rolled $n$ independent times, and then taking the limit of this probability as $n$ approaches infinity.

The probability of at least one match is given by $1 - (1 - \frac{1}{n})^n$. As $n$ increases without bound, the limit is:
\[
\lim_{n \to \infty} \left[ 1 - \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right)^n \right] = 1 - e^{-1} = 1 - \frac{1}{e}.
\]
Numerically, $e \approx 2.71828$, so $\frac{1}{e} \approx 0.367879$, and $1 - \frac{1}{e} \approx 0.632121$. The solution provides the answer as $0.632$, which is an approximation to three decimal places.

