Problem: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons of wavelength $300 \mathrm{~nm}$ and compare it with a typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.
Solution: The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{hcN_A}{\lambda}\), where \(h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J·s}\), \(c = 3.00 \times 10^8  \text{m/s}\), \(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23}  \text{mol}^{-1}\), and \(\lambda = 300  \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7}  \text{m}\).

First, calculate the energy per photon:  
\[E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19}  \text{J}\]

Then, for one mole of photons:  
\[E_{\text{mol}} = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5  \text{J/mol} = 399  \text{kJ/mol}\]

The wavelength \(300  \text{nm}\) has three significant figures, so the result is rounded to three significant figures.

Comparison with the typical single-bond energy of \(400  \text{kJ/mol}\):  
The photon energy of \(399  \text{kJ/mol}\) is very close to the bond energy, indicating that UV light of this wavelength can break such bonds.

Summary: The final answer is $399$
Extracted answer:
